The release operation is `reader.close()`, not `inputStreamReader.close()`. But `reader.close()` is a release operation *for the resource wrapped by `reader`*, i.e., for `inputStreamReader`. Since `inputStreamReader` is the underlying delegate, and `reader.close()` is guaranteed (via twr), this constitutes a *Sink* for `SRC`, because `SRC` (the `InputStreamReader`) is released *through* `reader.close()` — and `reader` is an alias (wrapper) of `SRC`. The spec says “track aliasing through assignments and argument passing”, and wrapper construction is aliasing (delegation). Moreover, `LineNumberReader`’s `close()` is part of the autocloseable lifecycle and is invoked *guaranteed* on all exits.

